uri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adam de Bury II was born about 1220, in Bury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Adam de Bury and Wife of Adam de Bury. He had at least 1 son with Anabel. He died after 1281, in his hometown."},"et":{"abt 1220–after 1281":"umbes 1220–pärast 1281","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1220–1281":"1220–1281","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1180–1275":"1180–1275","–Female":"Surnud","after 1280":"pärast 1280","after 1281":"pärast 1281","1275":"1275","1198